'''HMCS ''James Bay''''' ([[Hull classification symbol (Canada)|hull number]] MCB 152) was a {{sclass2-|Bay|minesweeper}} that was constructed for the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] during the [[Cold War]]. Entering service in 1954, the ship served on the [[British Columbia Coast|West Coast of Canada]] until 1964 when ''James Bay'' was [[Ship decommissioning|decommissioned]]. The minesweeper was sold in 1966 for use as an offshore oil exploration vessel.

==Design and description==
The Bay class were designed and ordered as replacements for the [[Second World War]]-era minesweepers that the Royal Canadian Navy operated at the time. Similar to the {{sclass2-|Ton|minesweeper|1}}, they were constructed of wood planking and aluminum framing.<ref name=m1>Macpherson and Barrie, p. 271</ref><ref name=con1>Gardiner and Chumbley, p. 49</ref>

[[Displacement (ship)|Displacing]] {{convert|390|LT|t}} standard at {{convert|412|LT|t}} at deep load, the minesweepers were {{convert|152|ft|m|abbr=on}} [[Length overall|long]] with a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|28|ft|m|abbr=on}} and a [[Draft (hull)|draught]] of {{convert|8|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=m1/><ref name=con1/> They had a complement of 38 officers and ratings.<ref name=m1/><ref group=note>Gardiner and Chumbley claim the complement was 40.</ref>

The Bay-class minesweepers were powered by two [[General Motors|GM]] 12-cylinder [[diesel engine]]s driving two shafts creating {{convert|2400|bhp|lk=in}}. This gave the ships a maximum speed of {{convert|16|kn|lk=in}} and a range of {{convert|3290|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|12|kn}}.<ref name=con1/><ref name=j1>Moore, p. 82</ref> The ships were armed with one [[40 mm Bofors]] gun and were equipped with minesweeping gear.<ref name=m1/><ref name=con1/>

==Operational history==
The ship's [[keel]] was laid down on 16 August 1951 by [[Yarrow Shipbuilders#Yarrows in Canada|Yarrows Ltd.]] at their yard in  [[Esquimalt, British Columbia|Esquimalt]], [[British Columbia]]. Initially named ''Chantry'', the vessel was renamed for a [[James Bay|bay]] located between [[Ontario]] and [[Quebec]] with islands that are part of [[Nunavut]] within.<ref name=c324>Colledge, p. 324</ref> ''James Bay'' was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 12 March 1953. The ship was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 3 May 1954.<ref name=mac275>Macpherson and Barrie, p. 275</ref>

The [[Second Canadian Minesweeping Squadron]] was formed in May 1954 at Esquimalt with {{HMCS|Comox|MCB 146|2}} and ''James Bay'' as the first two vessels of the unit.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Second Sweeper Squadron Formed |magazine=The Crowsnest |publisher=Queen's Printer |date=July 1954 |volume=6 |number=9 |pages=3}}</ref> Serving on the [[British Columbia Coast|West Coast of Canada]], in November 1955, the Second Canadian Minesweeping Squadron was among the Canadian units that took part a large naval exercise off the coast of [[California]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Biggest West Coast Exercises Held |magazine=The Crowsnest |publisher=Queen's Printer |location=Ottawa |date=December 1955 |volume=8 |number=2 |pages=2-3}}</ref> The Second Minesweeping Squadron, of which ''James Bay'' was a member made a port visit at [[Stockton, California]] in June 1960.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Second Minesweeping Squadron |magazine=The Crowsnest |publisher=Queen's Printer |location=Ottawa |date=November 1960 |volume=13 |number=1 |pages=24}}</ref> The vessel was [[Ship decommissioning|paid off]] on 28 February 1964. ''James Bay'' was sold to commercial interests in 1966 for use in offshore oil exploration.<ref name=mac275/><ref name=c324/>

